In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides were removed. Lifecycle events moved to the **`Window`** class. You have two main options:

### Option 1: Hook events in `CreateWindow` (quick)
```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* was OnStart   */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* was OnSleep   */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* was OnResume  */ };

    return window;
}
```

### Option 2: Subclass `Window` (cleaner for complex logic)
```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()  { base.OnCreated();  /* OnStart  */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()  { base.OnStopped();  /* OnSleep  */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()  { base.OnResumed();  /* OnResume */ }
}
```
Then in `App.xaml.cs`:
```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());
```

### Mapping summary

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Created` / `OnCreated()` |
| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `OnStopped()` |
| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed()` |

There are also `Activated`/`Deactivated` events if you need finer-grained focus tracking, and `ConfigureLifecycleEvents()` in `MauiProgram.cs` for **platform-specific** hooks (e.g., Android's `OnActivityResult`).
